<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-01-09T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-01-09T20:00:00-05:00" n="8" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d8">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/605: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the American Delegation</hi>
                                (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Davis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-01-10T01:00:00+00:00">January 10, 1936—1
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 9—9:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>40. Supplementing my 39, Jan. 9, 7 p.m.<note n="26" xml:id="d8fn26"><ref target="frus1936v01#pg_26">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                                    26</ref>.</note> Eden told me it was his opinion that the
                            so-called negotiations between China and Japan for a non-aggression pact
                            were not as serious a matter as Craigie thought and that in a talk with
                            the Chinese Ambassador he gathered the impression that the Chinese are
                            discussing this idea in order to play for time but without any serious
                            intention of consummating such a pact.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Davis</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>